opening time trial of the week-long race on Wednesday.</p><p>Omega clocked 20min 13sec over the 18.5-km (11.5-mile) route from Donoratico to San Vincenzo. It was an identical start from last year, when Cavendish also took the lead with an Omega win.</p><p>\"I'm happy,\" Cavendish said. \"The team is stronger than last year.\"</p><p>Cavendish has had a slow start to this season, with his only individual win coming in a stage of the Tour of Algarve last month.</p><p>The three-time time trial world champion Tony Martin was again the main engine behind Omega's success, which should benefit Michal Kwiatkowski and Rigoberto Urán, who are aiming for the overall win.</p><p>Orica Greenedge finished second, 11 seconds behind, and Movistar – featuring the Tour de France runner-up Nairo Quintana – were third, 18 seconds behind.</p><p>Alberto Contador's Tinkoff Saxo placed fourth, 24 seconds behind. Sky, with Bradley Wiggins and Richie Porte, were sixth, 27 seconds behind.</p><p>Porte was added to Sky's squad last week when the Tour de France winner <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/07/chris-froome-withdraws-tirreno-adriatico-injury\" title=\"\">Chris Froome</a> announced that he would miss the race due to a back injury.</p><p>Thursday's second stage is a 166km (103-mile) leg from San Vincenzo to Cascina that sets up well for sprinters.</p><p>The race, which includes a couple of uphill stages, ends on Tuesday with an individual time trial in San Benedetto del Tronto.</p><p>Many riders use it as a warmup for the Milan-San Remo classic, which is on 23 March.</p>","headline":"Mark Cavendish leads Tirreno-Adriatico after opening team time trial","trailText":"Mark Cavendish leads the Tirreno-Adriatico after Omega Pharma-Quick Step won the opening time trial by 11 seconds in San Vincenzo","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3nff2","wordcount":"242","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-15T17:53:02Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/12/mark