For an hour after the fall I kept feeling a strain on my knee every time I tried to accelerate. I went to see the doctor two or three times. In the end I didn't feel anything because of the adrenaline.\"</p><p>Germany's John Degenkolb led the pack in the final stretch as the riders prepared to go for the line. The Belgian rider Gianni Meersman attacked with about 100 metres to go and Bouhanni responded immediately to surge past him. Degenkolb subsequently overtook Meersman, who finished in third place.</p><p>The 162.5km (101-mile) stage started and finished in the Parisian suburb of Mantes-la-Jolie. The top three all clocked 3hr 53.11min.</p><p>The Frenchman Christophe Laborie opened up a lead of nine minutes after an early solo breakaway but was caught with 50km remaining. The American rider Tejay van Garderen, one of the favourites, dropped out during the stage after feeling unwell.</p><p>\"At night, I had all these stomach cramps, and bad diarrhoea all day yesterday and then a little bit of a fever and no appetite,\" he said.</p><p>\"It felt like my sickness was getting better and today I woke up and I felt OK. But I was really just empty. I couldn't take in calories and just had nothing in the muscles.\"</p><p>The defending champion Richie Porte pulled out in the days leading up to the race, focusing instead on the Tirreno-Adriatico race, saying it was more suited to his strengths and prompting an angry response from the Paris-Nice race director, Christian Prudhomme.</p><p>The Italian rider Vincenzo Nibali hopes to get his Tour de France preparations off to a good start with a strong performance here. He finished stage one tucked into the chasing pack in 35th place.</p><p>Monday's second stage is slightly longer, a 205km trek from Rambouillet to Saint-Georges-sur-Baulche.</p>","headline":"Nacer Bouhanni takes opening stage of Paris-Nice race despite falling","trailText":"The Frenchman Nacer Bouhanni won a three-way sprint finish to the opening stage of the Paris