to the Pringle, which will soon open to the public.  Photograph: Tom Jenkins/for the Observer","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Joanna Rowsell says double cycling gold in Colombia does not top London","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-08T21:59:00Z","sectionName":"Sport","sectionId":"sport","id":"sport/2014/mar/08/joanna-rowsell-cycling-gold-colombia-london","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3nce8","standfirst":"Fresh from a first world solo title in Cali, where she also shared in team pursuit success, the 25-year-old is still wowed by memories of 2012","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Joanna Rowsell is on top of the world and enjoying the ride. Having returned from the track cycling world championships in Colombia with her first gold medal in a major solo race, she has never had greater cause to celebrate. For an athlete who rarely stops grafting, that may not come easily.</p><p>\"It's still sinking in,\" Rowsell says of her double-gold haul in Cali, with success in the team and individual pursuits. \"We go there for the team pursuit and it means everything to the British girls. I would never take that away but the individual pursuit was so special for me. I have always dreamed about winning it.\"</p><p>The stunning win over the five-times champion Sarah Hammer represented a landmark in Rowsell's already impressive career. Her personal best time of 3min 30.318sec over 3km blew the American away, the final margin of victory a significant 1.2sec.</p><p>Yet, returning to the Olympic Park and the scene of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/04/gb-womens-team-pursuit-olympic-gold\" title=\"\">Britain's famous team gold in the London Velodrome</a>, Rowsell's brutal honesty about the trajectory of her career is cutting. \"People still ask me what has been my best ever victory and I always say London. Nothing will&nbsp;ever top that,\" she says. \"It's weird as an athlete to think that nothing will ever compare.\"</p><p>For some that insight could prove a major hindrance, the knowledge that it really will not get any better, no matter how much success is earned.</p><p>However, Rowsell's focus has been unwavering since 2012. The 25-year-old is a self-confessed workaholic, ambition and drive coursing through her veins with the same force as the lactic acid that burns track cyclists after an explosion of&nbsp;power.</p><p>Rio 2016 is at the front of her mind, as is the Commonwealth Games this summer. Going to Glasgow as an individual world champion provides renewed purpose but the chances of Rowsell taking her foot off the pedal are&nbsp;nonexistent.</p><p>\"There are always new challenges. I've still got plenty of ambition,\" she says. \"I don't know where it comes from. I'm a person [who] always wants to improve in everything I do.</p><p>\"If I ride to the track, I always challenge myself to get there quicker than last time and I'll probably be the same when I retire. People ask me how I stay motivated. I tell them that I just do.</p><p>\"It's hard for me to imagine not being as competitive as I am. I've seen other cyclists come and go from Britain's youth programme that have been talented but have not worked hard enough. Perhaps they don't have the same drive. I just can't imagine being like that.\"</p><p>Rowsell's will to win is what makes her such a fierce competitor. The knocks received on her path to the top would have destabilised the most hardened rider, yet to her they were merely obstacles to provide extra motivation.</p><p>In the space of six months in 2010 Rowsell crashed and knocked out her front two teeth. Then glandular fever left her bed-ridden and she broke her elbow on her return to action. \"I had a run of really bad luck,\" she says. \"There was a bad crash during training, blood everywhere. I looked like a freak – you know it's bad when you get to A&amp;E and everybody is staring at you. Then I got glandular fever and when I got back on the bike I broke my elbow.</p><p>\"I was left out of the squad and that year also coincided with the emergence of Laura Trott and Dani King. Everyone was like 'Wow we've got these two young girls who are really talented' and along with a few others [they] were billed as the ones to represent Britain at the&nbsp;Olympics.</p><p>\"I think some of the British Cycling coaches wrote me off. But I never lost belief in myself even though everybody else did. I had to work hard and prove myself to get back in the team. There are always knocks but you need to keep&nbsp;believing.\"</p><p>It is a mantra that Rowsell lives by. In her role as an ambassador for the London Youth Games she hopes to pass on the same message to young athletes aspiring to glory, be it in cycling or other&nbsp;sports.</p><p>Rowsell recalls how, in her first competitive race on a bike, she was the slowest of those competing. Now, as a world champion, the doubters have been proved wrong.</p><p>\"My first bike race wasn't great, I was the slowest. But I was told I had raw talent,\" Rowsell says. \"You have to work. There are days when you don't want to go out in the pouring rain for four hours: that's normal. I just think about the chocolate I'll have when I get  home.\"</p><p>Even against Hammer Rowsell was the underdog, yet the fact she was not expected to win again fed her desire. \"People thought she was going to catch me. But I knew I had the legs. I was in the perfect zone – confident and relaxed. There was no pressure on me. When I won it wasn't relief it was pure happiness.</p><p>\"I had a second's lead after one lap, which I pretty much maintained. I had to go round a few laps of the track before I knew I'd won.</p><p>\"It was amazing. I had a huge smile on my face and the first person I saw once I got off the track was Chris Hoy. I think he was quite surprised.\"</p><p>After co-commentating for BT Sport at the Revolution meeting in the Velodrome that starts on Friday, Rowsell will turn her attention to the road with the Wiggle Honda team before focusing on the track before the Commonwealth Games. \"I can definitely go quicker. The most important thing is to believe in yourself,\" she says, before revealing the personal significance of her victory in Colombia.</p><p>\"It was weird being on the podium on my own, and a different feeling knowing that you are the best in the world, thinking what that actually means. This was me, on my own. It felt incredibly special.\"</p><p><em>Joanna Rowsell is a patron of the 2014 Balfour Beatty London Youth Games</em></p>","headline":"Joanna Rowsell says double cycling gold in Colombia does not top London","trailText":"<p>Fresh from a first world solo title in Cali, where she also shared in team pursuit success, the 25-year-old is still wowed by memories of 2012, she tells James Riach</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/pictures/2014/3/8/1394305862056/Joanna-Rowsell-003.jpg","wordcount":"997","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-11T21:59:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/08/joanna-rowsell-cycling-gold-colombia-london","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/mar/08/joanna-rowsell-cycling-gold-colombia-london","tags":[{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sport","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/sport","references":[]},{"id":"profile/james-riach","webTitle":"James Riach","r2ContributorId":"49942","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/13/1376408310613/JamesRiach.jpg","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>James Riach is a sports journalist for the Guardian, specialising in football. He is based in London</p>","webUr